summary.seg: During the medieval period, history did not officially form part of the curriculum taught at universities. However, it fulfilled an important ancillary role to theology, one of the higher faculties of study. According to the writings of Hugh of St Victor (c. 1096-1141), a canon of the abbey of St Victor in Paris, there were three approaches to reading the Scriptures: historical, allegorical and tropological. Hugh reasoned that history - in the sense of the correct sequence of past events, but also the literal sense of any narrative, and both with specific reference to the Bible - was the foundation upon which must rest any subsequent figurative interpretation of the Bible as a source of moral guidance. To this end, Hugh advocated the training of one's memory and the use of mnemonic techniques. These were complemented by simultaneous changes in the presentation of texts in manuscripts: specifically, the creation of paratextual apparatus and visual cues to facilitate the accessing and comprehension of the text they accompanied, or another to which it referred, by their readers.

The individual contents of this manuscript, their selection for compilation within a single volume, and the manner in which they were presented illustrate the development and dissemination of these new intellectual and bibliographical trends. It comprises three texts, the first two of which were composed to aid the understanding of biblical history: the Historia scholastica of Peter Comestor (d. 1187) and the Genealogia historiarum (or Compendium historiae in genealogia Christi) of Peter of Poitiers (c. 1130-c. 1205). The third text, the Allegoriae in uetus testamentum, was written by Richard of St Victor (d. 1173), a pupil of Hugh's, and exemplifies the figurative modes of reading the Bible by describing the allegorical meanings to be found in the names of people, places or events related in the Old Testament.

The Historia scholastica occupies the bulk of this manuscript, and the text represents an attempt to put Hugh of St Victor's ideas into practice. Comestor organised his narrative according to the order of the books of the Bible, with each of its constituent histories corresponding to a biblical book or collection of books, and thus providing the reader with a historical foundation for the study of the scriptures. In many places, the Historia was presented using parallel columns, which enabled Comestor to accommodate his incidental observations without interrupting the framework of the events narrated in the Bible. In this manuscript, these take the form of improvised sub-columns, their text demarcated from the rest by rubricated lines that appear to have been drawn freehand and after the text had been copied (see f. 16r for extensive examples in both columns, and note how the rubricated line frequently runs over parts of letters).

Similar experimentation with layout is found in the first text in this manuscript, the Compendium historiae in genealogia Christi of Peter of Poitiers. The two authors were close contemporaries - Comestor served as Chancellor of Notre Dame and Dean of the cathedral school, before being succeeded by Peter of Poitiers in 1169 - and their two texts commonly accompanied one another in manuscripts. Although in this manuscript the Compendium is apparently of separate production - on a separate quire of six leaves (constrasting with the quires of eight found in the rest of the book), its text copied by a different hand, and decorated with a different set of pigments that have in places corroded the parchment (such damage not being found elsewhere) - there is no reason to suppose that they were not produced around the same time and with the intention from the outset or at an early stage that they should be bound together in a single volume. Poitiers' work is essentially a family tree: it condenses Old Testament history in order to illustrate Jesus's descent from Adam. In this manuscript, the names of individuals are enclosed in roundels, the most important being picked out in gold, and their relationship to one another is shown by interconnecting coloured lines. Interspersed among the parts of the genealogy are multiple columns of text, providing the reader with additional information concerning specific people, places or historical events. There are also schematic diagrams: first of Noah's ark (one derived from description in the Book of Genesis; and one from the 1st-century Jewish historian Josephus's Antiquitates iudaicae), then the three mansions in the desert and the Tabernacle, and finally the habitation of the king and priests of Israel. In keeping with Hugh of St Victor's precepts, these illustrations - and the genealogical diagrams as a whole - were intended as aids to memory, providing visual points of reference for the mental arrangement of historical information transmitted to the reader in the text.

The close association of these two texts appears to have led at an early stage to the expansion of the Compendium with material from the Historia scholastica as well as other sources (the range of illustrations also varied in later, expanded versions). This manuscript is notable as perhaps the earliest extant copy of the 'interpolated' version of the Compendium made in England. Dating to the late 12th century, it furthermore illustrates the rapid dissemination of these new intellectual currents from the University of Paris to centres of scholarship elsewhere in Europe.

Dr James Freeman
Medieval Manuscripts Specialist
Cambridge University Library

foliation.note: Numbering in pencil in the upper right-hand corner of the rectos.

collation.signatures: Quires 2-31 signed 'I'-'XXVII', 'XXIX-XXXI' on the verso of the last leaf of each quire. No text is missing between Quires 'XXVII' and 'XXIX'.

The leaves of the first half of a quire are often marked in plummet in the lower margin with what appears to be an early form of bifolium signature. It consists of a 'bifolium catchword' (a word or part of a word that matches the opening word on the recto of the next leaf) and / or a symbol or lower-case letter specific to that quire and which is repeated in the lower margin of the recto of the next leaf.
collation.catchwords: Catchwords, in the lower right-hand corner of the verso of the last leaf of each quire

condition.p: The manuscript is grimy throughout. The red, green and blue pigment is often rubbed off or abraded in varying degrees of severity (see ff. 16r, 18r, 127v, 149r and 257r). There staining, largely in the upper part of the leaves, which worsens towards the rear of the manuscript (see ff. 261 and 278-279). There are a number of leaves with areas that have been turned in and which now protrude beyond the edges of the leaves, which indicates that the manuscript has been trimmed (see ff. 88r). The manuscript has suffered from excessive rounding and the addition of a large amount of adhesive on the spine (see, for example, ff. 102-103, which has induced a considerable amount of cockling, pleating and folding of the leaves (see ff. 240, 243 and 247). The last leaf is mutilated (f. 285), with loss of text.

Quire 1 is in a particularly fragile condition (ff. 1-6), owing to the use of verdigris in the green pigment for some of the lines of descent. In places, this has burnt through the parchment, leaving the surrounding area brittle and vulnerable to loss and tearing. Portions of the lower edges and corners are also missing, perhaps also as a consequence of burn-through.
At the time of cataloguing (January 2020), the manuscript remains unbound.

layoutDesc.layout: 1r-6r: Pricking marks visible only in the gutter. Ruled in leadpoint, in two columns, text wrapped around genealogical diagrams, written above top line.

Ruled in leadpoint, frame and line. Two columns, 45 lines to the page, written above top line. Pricking marks visible only in the gutter.

decoDesc.decoNote: 1r-6r: Genealogical tables from Adam to Christ, of Jewish kings and prophets, rulers of Mesopotamia, Persia and Egypt, Alexander the Great and Roman emperors, some names encircled in gold.

Diagrams with gilding:
1r: two schematic depictions of Noah's ark, 'secundum moysen' and 'secundum iosephum'
2r: mansions in the desert and Tabernacle
4v: habitatio regis et sacerdotum

decoNote.p: Red, green or blue initials with penwork flourishing (5-28 lines), some filled with foliage, at the beginning of each book.
Red, blue and green chapter initials (3 lines), some with penwork flourishing in alternating colours.

Human and animal heads or figures in lower margins marking run-overs and occasionally associated with the text: e.g. Adam plangens (13r), man with shield (39r), eagle (47v), goat with inscription peccata populi (60r).

binding.p: Brown calfskin, blind-tooled, over paste-laminate boards, perhaps late 17th century.
binding.condition: Rebacked during the 20th century; presently disbound.
